===Virulence===
H5N1 has [[mutation|mutated]] into a variety of [[strain (biology)|strains]] with differing pathogenic profiles, some pathogenic to one species but not others, some pathogenic to multiple species. Each specific known genetic variation is traceable to a virus isolate of a specific case of infection. Through [[antigenic drift]], H5N1 has mutated into dozens of highly pathogenic varieties divided into genetic clades which are known from specific isolates, but all currently belonging to genotype Z of avian influenza virus H5N1, now the dominant genotype.<ref name=WHOinfluenza>

{{cite journal
| author=The World Health Organization Global Influenza Program Surveillance Network. | title=Evolution of H5N1 avian influenza viruses in Asia | journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases | year=2005 | volume=11 | issue=10 | url=http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/EID/vol11no10/05-0644.htm | pmid=16318689
| pages=1515–21
}}
<br/> ''Figure 1 shows a diagramatic representation of the genetic relatedness of Asian H5N1 [[hemagglutinin]] genes from various isolates of the virus''
</ref><ref name=Kou>

