| doi=10.1128/JVI.79.24.15460-15466.2005
| pmc=1316012
}}
</ref> H5N1 isolates found in [[Hong Kong]] in 1997 and 2001 were not consistently transmitted efficiently among birds and did not cause significant disease in these animals. In 2002, new isolates of H5N1 were appearing within the bird population of Hong Kong. These new isolates caused acute disease, including severe neurological dysfunction and death in [[duck]]s. This was the first reported case of lethal influenza virus infection in wild aquatic birds since 1961.<ref name=Sturm>

{{cite journal
| author=Sturm-Ramirez KM, Ellis T, Bousfield B, Bissett L, Dyrting K, Rehg JE, Poon L, Guan Y, Peiris M, Webster RG. | title=Reemerging H5N1 Influenza Viruses in Hong Kong in 2002 Are Highly Pathogenic to Ducks | journal=J. Virol. | year=2004 | pages=4892–4901 | volume=78 | issue=9 | pmid=15078970
